pf <- read.delim('pseudo_facebook.tsv')

#qplot syntax
#qplot(age, friend_count, data = pf)

#ggplot syntax

ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count), data = pf) +
    geom_point() +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(13,100), breaks = seq(0,100,5))
## Warning: Removed 3687 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

What are some things that you notice right away?

Response: Younger people tend to have more friends on average. There are some outliers at a few specific ages.

ggplot Syntax

Notes: ggplot syntax is more verbose than qplot, must wrap variables in aes() wrapper.

#adding xlim
ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count), data = pf) +
    geom_point() +
    xlim(13,90)
## Warning: Removed 4906 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

    #scale_x_continuous(limits = c(13,100), breaks = seq(0,100,5))

Overplotting

Notes: overplotting makes it hard to distinguish the graphs characteristics, can use alpha level to change transparency

ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count), data = pf) +
    #alpha allows you to see the distribution of data points, takes 20 data points for a point in the graph to be completely dark
    #jitter introduces some noise to the data, breaking up the lines seen in the first graph above
    geom_jitter(alpha = 1/20) +
    xlim(13,90)
## Warning: Removed 5178 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

What do you notice in the plot?

Response: Most of the under-25 crowd has less than 100 friends.

Coord_trans()

Notes:Cartesian coordinate system transformation

ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count), data = pf) +
    geom_point(alpha = 1/20) +
    xlim(13,90) +
    coord_trans(y = 'sqrt')
## Warning: Removed 4906 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Look up the documentation for coord_trans() and add a layer to the plot that transforms friend_count using the square root function. Create your plot!

#redoing the above plot with jitter
ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count), data = pf) +
    geom_point(alpha = 1/20, position = position_jitter(h=0)) +
    xlim(13,90) +
    coord_trans(y = 'sqrt')
## Warning: Removed 5187 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Overlaying Summaries with Raw Data

Notes:

ggplot(aes(x=age, y=friend_count), data = pf) +
    coord_cartesian(xlim = c(13, 90), ylim = c(0,1000)) +
    #xlim(13,90) +
    geom_point(alpha = 1/20, 
               position = position_jitter(h=0),
               color = 'orange') +
    #coord_trans(y = 'sqrt') +
    geom_line(stat = 'summary', fun.y = mean) +
    geom_line(stat = 'summary', fun.y = quantile, fun.args = list(probs = .1), linetype = 2, color = 'blue') +
    geom_line(stat = 'summary', fun.y = quantile, fun.args = list(probs = .9), linetype = 2, color = 'blue') +
    geom_line(stat = 'summary', fun.y = quantile, fun.args = list(probs = .5), color = 'blue')

What are some of your observations of the plot?

Response: There are definite outliers around 95 to 100 years old.

Noise in Conditional Means

    geom_line() +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1,71,5))

Smoothing Conditional Means

Notes:

p1 <- ggplot(aes(x = age_with_months, y = friend_count_mean), data = subset(pf.fc_by_age_in_months, age_with_months < 71)) +
    geom_line() +
    geom_smooth() +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1,71,5))

p2 <- ggplot(aes(x = age, y = friend_count_mean), data = subset(pf.fc_by_age2, age < 71)) +
    geom_line() +
    geom_smooth() +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1,71,5))

p3 <- ggplot(aes(x = round(age / 5) * 5, y = friend_count),
             data = subset(pf, age < 71)) +
    geom_line(stat = 'summary', fun.y = mean)
